<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="88" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph blockId="1.[136,1083,820,847]" box="[136,1083,820,847]" pageId="1" pageNumber="88">
<heading box="[136,1083,820,847]" fontSize="11" level="2" pageId="1" pageNumber="88" reason="3">
<taxonomicName authority="M.Rybak, Kochman-Kedziora, Luthfi" authorityName="M. Rybak, Kochman-Kedziora, Luthfi" authorityYear="2022" box="[136,851,820,847]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Naviculaceae" genus="Microcostatus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="1" pageNumber="88" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="labrisicus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[136,418,820,847]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="88">Microcostatus labrisicus</emphasis>
M.Rybak, Kochman-Kędziora, Luthfi
</taxonomicName>
, 
<emphasis box="[862,947,821,846]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="88">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[862,947,821,846]" pageId="1" pageNumber="88" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[961,1074,820,846]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–19" captionStartId="2.[136,243,1899,1921]" captionTargetBox="[152,1436,211,1875]" captionTargetId="figure-21@2.[151,1436,209,1875]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–19. Microcostatus labrisicus sp. nov. Figs 1–13. Light micrographs of the holotype population, fig. 7 represents the holotype specimen. Figs 14–17. Scanning electron microscopic (SEM) images of external view. Fig. 14. External view of the entire valve. Fig. 15. External detail of the central area and central parts of longitudinal depressions. Figs 16–17. External detail of the distal raphe endings and microcostae. Fig. 18. Internal detail of the central area and proximal raphe endings. Fig. 19. Internal valve view. Scale barrepresents 5 µm (Figs 1–13), 4 µm (Fig. 14), 3 µm (Fig. 19), 1 µm (Figs 15–18)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6875693" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6875693/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="88">Figs 1–19</figureCitation>
)
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[136,1452,892,1891]" pageId="1" pageNumber="88">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[136,484,892,918]" pageId="1" pageNumber="88">
LM observations (
<figureCitation box="[361,476,892,918]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–19" captionStartId="2.[136,243,1899,1921]" captionTargetBox="[152,1436,211,1875]" captionTargetId="figure-21@2.[151,1436,209,1875]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–19. Microcostatus labrisicus sp. nov. Figs 1–13. Light micrographs of the holotype population, fig. 7 represents the holotype specimen. Figs 14–17. Scanning electron microscopic (SEM) images of external view. Fig. 14. External view of the entire valve. Fig. 15. External detail of the central area and central parts of longitudinal depressions. Figs 16–17. External detail of the distal raphe endings and microcostae. Fig. 18. Internal detail of the central area and proximal raphe endings. Fig. 19. Internal valve view. Scale barrepresents 5 µm (Figs 1–13), 4 µm (Fig. 14), 3 µm (Fig. 19), 1 µm (Figs 15–18)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6875693" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6875693/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="88">Fig. 1–13</figureCitation>
)
</emphasis>
: 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[492,520,892,918]" pageId="1" pageNumber="88">—</emphasis>
Valves lanceolate to elliptical-lanceolate with convex valve margins and slightly protracted apices. Valve dimensions (n=25): length 6.0–8.5 µm, width 3.0–3.5 µm, length/width ratio 2.0–2.6. Striae invisible in light microscopy. Raphe branches straight. Proximal raphe and distal raphe endings barely visible. The shape of central area only visible in SEM, visible in LM as labrys-shaped shadow.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="88" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="1.[136,1452,892,1891]" pageId="1" pageNumber="88">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,567,1036,1062]" pageId="1" pageNumber="88">
SEM observations (
<figureCitation box="[430,559,1036,1062]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–19" captionStartId="2.[136,243,1899,1921]" captionTargetBox="[152,1436,211,1875]" captionTargetId="figure-21@2.[151,1436,209,1875]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–19. Microcostatus labrisicus sp. nov. Figs 1–13. Light micrographs of the holotype population, fig. 7 represents the holotype specimen. Figs 14–17. Scanning electron microscopic (SEM) images of external view. Fig. 14. External view of the entire valve. Fig. 15. External detail of the central area and central parts of longitudinal depressions. Figs 16–17. External detail of the distal raphe endings and microcostae. Fig. 18. Internal detail of the central area and proximal raphe endings. Fig. 19. Internal valve view. Scale barrepresents 5 µm (Figs 1–13), 4 µm (Fig. 14), 3 µm (Fig. 19), 1 µm (Figs 15–18)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6875693" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6875693/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="88">Fig. 14–19</figureCitation>
)
</emphasis>
: 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[575,603,1036,1062]" pageId="1" pageNumber="88">—</emphasis>
Striae radiate (~ 
<quantity box="[788,850,1036,1063]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.27" pageId="1" pageNumber="88" unit="in" value="50.0">50 in</quantity>
10 µm), composed of one row of round to slightly elongated areolae, externally not occluded (
<figureCitation box="[627,758,1072,1099]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–19" captionStartId="2.[136,243,1899,1921]" captionTargetBox="[152,1436,211,1875]" captionTargetId="figure-21@2.[151,1436,209,1875]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–19. Microcostatus labrisicus sp. nov. Figs 1–13. Light micrographs of the holotype population, fig. 7 represents the holotype specimen. Figs 14–17. Scanning electron microscopic (SEM) images of external view. Fig. 14. External view of the entire valve. Fig. 15. External detail of the central area and central parts of longitudinal depressions. Figs 16–17. External detail of the distal raphe endings and microcostae. Fig. 18. Internal detail of the central area and proximal raphe endings. Fig. 19. Internal valve view. Scale barrepresents 5 µm (Figs 1–13), 4 µm (Fig. 14), 3 µm (Fig. 19), 1 µm (Figs 15–18)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6875693" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6875693/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="88">Figs 14, 15</figureCitation>
). Central area large, labrys-shape, bordered by ~10 shortened striae (often with only one areola) positioned on both sides, close to the valve margins. Raphe straight, filiform, located in raised constricted sternum with much reduced conopeum (
<figureCitation box="[826,958,1144,1171]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–19" captionStartId="2.[136,243,1899,1921]" captionTargetBox="[152,1436,211,1875]" captionTargetId="figure-21@2.[151,1436,209,1875]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–19. Microcostatus labrisicus sp. nov. Figs 1–13. Light micrographs of the holotype population, fig. 7 represents the holotype specimen. Figs 14–17. Scanning electron microscopic (SEM) images of external view. Fig. 14. External view of the entire valve. Fig. 15. External detail of the central area and central parts of longitudinal depressions. Figs 16–17. External detail of the distal raphe endings and microcostae. Fig. 18. Internal detail of the central area and proximal raphe endings. Fig. 19. Internal valve view. Scale barrepresents 5 µm (Figs 1–13), 4 µm (Fig. 14), 3 µm (Fig. 19), 1 µm (Figs 15–18)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6875693" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6875693/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="88">Figs 14, 15</figureCitation>
). Conopeum wider near the proximal raphe endings, tapering towards apices. Proximal raphe fissures widely separated lying in spathulate lipped grooves (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 1–19" captionStartId="2.[136,243,1899,1921]" captionTargetBox="[152,1436,211,1875]" captionTargetId="figure-21@2.[151,1436,209,1875]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–19. Microcostatus labrisicus sp. nov. Figs 1–13. Light micrographs of the holotype population, fig. 7 represents the holotype specimen. Figs 14–17. Scanning electron microscopic (SEM) images of external view. Fig. 14. External view of the entire valve. Fig. 15. External detail of the central area and central parts of longitudinal depressions. Figs 16–17. External detail of the distal raphe endings and microcostae. Fig. 18. Internal detail of the central area and proximal raphe endings. Fig. 19. Internal valve view. Scale barrepresents 5 µm (Figs 1–13), 4 µm (Fig. 14), 3 µm (Fig. 19), 1 µm (Figs 15–18)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6875693" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6875693/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="88">Fig. 15</figureCitation>
). Distal raphe fissures hooked and deflected to the same side (
<figureCitation box="[882,1015,1216,1242]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–19" captionStartId="2.[136,243,1899,1921]" captionTargetBox="[152,1436,211,1875]" captionTargetId="figure-21@2.[151,1436,209,1875]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–19. Microcostatus labrisicus sp. nov. Figs 1–13. Light micrographs of the holotype population, fig. 7 represents the holotype specimen. Figs 14–17. Scanning electron microscopic (SEM) images of external view. Fig. 14. External view of the entire valve. Fig. 15. External detail of the central area and central parts of longitudinal depressions. Figs 16–17. External detail of the distal raphe endings and microcostae. Fig. 18. Internal detail of the central area and proximal raphe endings. Fig. 19. Internal valve view. Scale barrepresents 5 µm (Figs 1–13), 4 µm (Fig. 14), 3 µm (Fig. 19), 1 µm (Figs 15–18)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6875693" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6875693/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="88">Figs 16, 17</figureCitation>
). Longitudinal depressions, narrowing towards the apices positioned on both sides of sternum, separated by thickened fascia. Small microcostae with irregular silica granules visible in longitudinal depressions. A single row of rounded to slightly elongated pores present on the valve mantle (
<figureCitation box="[295,468,1324,1350]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–19" captionStartId="2.[136,243,1899,1921]" captionTargetBox="[152,1436,211,1875]" captionTargetId="figure-21@2.[151,1436,209,1875]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–19. Microcostatus labrisicus sp. nov. Figs 1–13. Light micrographs of the holotype population, fig. 7 represents the holotype specimen. Figs 14–17. Scanning electron microscopic (SEM) images of external view. Fig. 14. External view of the entire valve. Fig. 15. External detail of the central area and central parts of longitudinal depressions. Figs 16–17. External detail of the distal raphe endings and microcostae. Fig. 18. Internal detail of the central area and proximal raphe endings. Fig. 19. Internal valve view. Scale barrepresents 5 µm (Figs 1–13), 4 µm (Fig. 14), 3 µm (Fig. 19), 1 µm (Figs 15–18)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6875693" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6875693/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="88">Figs 14, 16, 17</figureCitation>
). Internally areolae are clearly separated and not occluded by hymenes, striae separated by slightly thickened virgae. Raphe branches straight with spathulate proximal raphe endings. The central area is broad, bow-tie in shape (
<figureCitation box="[414,543,1396,1422]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–19" captionStartId="2.[136,243,1899,1921]" captionTargetBox="[152,1436,211,1875]" captionTargetId="figure-21@2.[151,1436,209,1875]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–19. Microcostatus labrisicus sp. nov. Figs 1–13. Light micrographs of the holotype population, fig. 7 represents the holotype specimen. Figs 14–17. Scanning electron microscopic (SEM) images of external view. Fig. 14. External view of the entire valve. Fig. 15. External detail of the central area and central parts of longitudinal depressions. Figs 16–17. External detail of the distal raphe endings and microcostae. Fig. 18. Internal detail of the central area and proximal raphe endings. Fig. 19. Internal valve view. Scale barrepresents 5 µm (Figs 1–13), 4 µm (Fig. 14), 3 µm (Fig. 19), 1 µm (Figs 15–18)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6875693" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6875693/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="88">Figs 18, 19</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
